I think we're coming closer together.  I'd just press on a few things:

(1) saying our judicial system is based on "facts" is only the start of the question, not the end.  if you have a trial, you have evidence that has to be interpreted, and most of all what you have is testimony -- basically, people telling you what they understand to have happened.  In a very real sense, it really is just the "words" of people who were there, or who know something about the topic at issue, and yet that's enough for very serious decisions.  Criminal convictions can be based entirely on circumstantial evidence, there's no requirement someone firsthand observed the crime, and of course none of the jurors would have seen it firsthand, but the decision is ultimately in their hands.

Indeed, the very reason for the jury system is that different people bring different personal experiences to the decisionmaking process.  The idea is that, with that many people hearing the testimony, seeing the evidence, and talking about what it means filtered through their own experience, we should get a better result than just one person with their necessarily limited worldview coming to a decision.

(2) studies come in all shapes and forms, but personal experience is going to shape them at a number of levels.  in the design of a scientific study, in the way someone interprets the facts in a historical study, etc.  and most of all, the way someone perceives a study's results is going to be shaped by their own experiences and prior knowledge.  Neither you nor I would pick up every study we read and say "this is 100% correct because it's a study."  We have our own experiences that are going to lead us to reject some conclusions, even if in study form.  It's completely natural.

&amp;#x200B;

In the end, I don't disagree that being entirely inflexible in your own opinions, or acting like they could never change and must be correct, is dangerous.  But I think part of that process is realizing how much all of our opinions, beliefs, and understandings and interpretations of facts are based in some large part on our personal experiences, whether we consciously recognize it or not.  We can't go around all day discounting our personal experiences as a means to help make judgments large and small, from what clothes to wear today to where to park your car to what house to buy to how to vote in an election.  We'd be paralyzed if we couldn't use our own experiences to drive decisionmaking all around us.  and for a great number of things, because of time or lack of experience or lack of available exposure to other inputs, our experiences are going to be all we have.  It's imperfect, absolutely, but recognizing this is an important part of ALL decisionmaking is a super important part of keeping an open mind.

&amp;#x200B;

